                <head>384. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, White House Tapes,
                    Recording of conversation between <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName>
                    and <persName corresp="#p_HBMJ1">Haig</persName>, January 10, 1972, 5:31–5:48
                    p.m., Old Executive Office Building, Conversation No. 313–30. No classification
                    marking.</p>
                <p>On January 10, President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> discussed
                    the upshot of the crisis in South Asia with his Deputy Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs, <persName corresp="#p_HBMJ1">Alexander Haig</persName>. With
                    regard to the question of the recognition of Bangladesh, <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> asked when Pakistan and China were likely
                    to recognize the new government. “Don’t we have to wait,” he said, “until they
                    do.” He noted that “everybody else is jumping on the bandwagon,” making specific
                    reference to Britain and France. <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName>
                    agreed with <persName corresp="#p_HBMJ1">Haig</persName> that the United States
                    should move cautiously on the issue.</p>
            </div>
